Would you like a short snippet showing how to implement a light/dark theme toggle using those variables?

user:
Here’s a simple method for a light/dark theme toggle that works with the color variables you’ve set up. It uses only a bit of CSS and JavaScript.

---

### **1. Extend your CSS variables**

```css
:root {
  --color-bg: #ffffff;
  --color-text: #2f2f2f;
  --color-accent: #2a7ae2;
  --color-muted: #555555;
  --color-panel: #f5f7fa;
}

/* Dark theme overrides */
[data-theme="dark"] {
  --color-bg: #000000;
  --color-text: #ffffff;
  --color-accent: #64b5f6;
  --color-muted: #cccccc;
  --color-panel: #1a1a1a;
}

/* Body styles read from variables */
body {
  background: var(--color-bg);
  color: var(--color-text);
  transition: background 0.3s ease, color 0.3s ease;
}
```

---

### **2. Add a small toggle button**

```html
<button id="theme-toggle" aria-label="Toggle light and dark theme">
  🌙 Dark / ☀️ Light
</button>
```

---

### **3. JavaScript to switch themes**

```js
const toggle = document.getElementById('theme-toggle');
toggle.addEventListener('click', () => {
  const currentTheme = document.documentElement.getAttribute('data-theme');
  const newTheme = currentTheme === 'dark' ? 'light' : 'dark';
  document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', newTheme);
  localStorage.setItem('theme', newTheme);
});

// Load stored preference on page load
const savedTheme = localStorage.getItem('theme');
if (savedTheme) {
  document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', savedTheme);
}
```

---

This setup:
- Adds smooth transitions between schemes.  
- Saves the user’s choice so it persists on revisit.  
- Works without third‑party libraries.  

It’s a lightweight, accessible way to give readers control over contrast and comfort on your resource site.

Would you like me to include an optional CSS media query that auto‑detects system preference (`prefers-color-scheme`)?

assistant:
Good thought — adding that media query makes the toggle feel modern and respectful of a user’s settings.

Here’s the small addition that lets your page start in the visitor’s preferred mode:

```css
/* Detect system preference and set initial theme */
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  :root {
    color-scheme: dark;
  }
  body {
    background: #000000;
    color: #ffffff;
  }
}
```

If you want full consistency with your variable setup, you can couple the detection with the attribute system:

```js
// On load, check both stored setting and system preference
const savedTheme = localStorage.getItem('theme');
if (savedTheme) {
  document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', savedTheme);
} else {
  const prefersDark = window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)').matches;
  document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', prefersDark ? 'dark' : 'light');
}
```

**Accessibility tips**

- Ensure the toggle button stays visible in both themes (use a neutral border or outline).  
- Label it clearly: “Switch between light and dark mode.”  
- Announce changes to screen readers if you’re refining later (`aria-live="polite"` on a status span).

That completes a smooth, ethical, and accessible theme system for your educational communication‑skills site.
